;; =============================================================================
;; Spec: Policy Pack Compilation — Implementation Work Spec
;; =============================================================================
;;
;; Normative contract: specs/normative/N4-delta-policy-compilation-contract.md
;; Informative notes:  specs/informative/I-CANDIDATE-REVIEW-WORKFLOW.md
;;                     specs/informative/I-PACK-ATTACHMENT-PRECEDENCE.md
;;
;; This work spec covers the first implementation of the policy compilation
;; pipeline. It operates under the normative contract defined in N4-delta,
;; which standardizes the candidate model, provenance, promotion rules,
;; and compilation guarantees.
;;
;; Problem:
;;
;;   Adoption stalls at the cold-start problem. Organizations already have
;;   their standards — style guides, security policies, SOC2 compliance docs,
;;   accessibility requirements — but they exist as natural-language documents,
;;   not enforceable policy packs. Miniforge should not require organizations
;;   to rewrite themselves into policy packs by hand before they can adopt
;;   governed workflows. It should compile policy from organizational reality
;;   into reviewable, provenance-backed artifacts.
;;
;; Relationship to other specs:
;;
;;   - N4-delta-policy-compilation-contract.md — normative contract that
;;     constrains this work spec (candidate model, provenance, promotion)
;;   - policy-pack-extensibility.spec.edn — pack schema this targets
;;   - policy-pack-configuration.spec.edn — how compiled packs attach to repos
;;   - repo-config-profile.spec.edn — repo config declares pack references

{:spec/title "Compile policy packs from organizational documents"

 :spec/description
 "Implement the policy pack compilation pipeline per the N4-delta normative
  contract. Three modes: compile, derive, compose. All modes produce candidate
  artifacts first; final pack emission happens after review or auto-promotion.

  MODE 1: COMPILE (document → candidates → pack)
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────
  Input:  One or more organizational documents (markdown, PDF, plaintext,
          HTML, or URL). Examples: style guide, security policy, SOC2 controls,
          accessibility standards, code review checklist.

  Process:
  - Parse and chunk the document into sections
  - LLM extracts discrete policy obligations from each section
  - Each obligation becomes a candidate with:
      candidate/id, candidate/statement, candidate/category,
      candidate/origin-type (:direct), candidate/enforceability,
      candidate/status (:proposed), candidate/provenance
  - Optional: attach candidate/check-hint for later executable realization
  - Candidates are deduplicated and grouped by category
  - Output: policy-candidates.edn (reviewable candidate artifact)
  - After review: accepted candidates promote into .pack.edn

  CLI:
    miniforge policy compile <source> --emit candidates
    miniforge policy compile <source> --review
    miniforge policy compile <source> --promote

  MODE 2: DERIVE (repo → candidates → pack)
  ──────────────────────────────────────────
  Input:  A repository path (or the current working directory).

  Process:
  - Scan existing linter configs (.clj-kondo, .eslintrc, .pylintrc, etc.)
  - Scan CI config (.github/workflows, .gitlab-ci.yml) for enforced checks
  - Scan git history for commit message conventions, PR templates
  - Scan existing .editorconfig, .prettierrc, formatting configs
  - Directly machine-readable artifacts produce candidates WITHOUT LLM
  - Optional --enrich flag uses LLM to add natural-language descriptions
  - Each candidate has origin-type :inferred and source provenance
  - Output: policy-candidates.edn with repo-artifact provenance

  CLI:
    miniforge policy derive [repo-path] --emit candidates
    miniforge policy derive [repo-path] --enrich
    miniforge policy derive [repo-path] --promote

  MODE 3: COMPOSE (packs → pack)  [pure, deterministic, no LLM]
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Input:  A composition spec — a list of base packs with overrides.

  Process:
  - Load each base pack
  - Apply overrides: disable rules, change severity, add custom rules
  - Resolve conflicts deterministically per precedence model
  - Merge rules, preserving contributing provenance from all upstream packs
  - Output: a single flattened .pack.edn

  This is pure pack algebra — no candidates, no LLM, deterministic.

  Composition spec (EDN):
  {:base-packs    ['foundations-1.0.0' 'org-security-v2']
   :disable-rules [:rule/some-rule-id]
   :override      {:rule/max-function-length {:severity :warning
                                               :threshold 50}}
   :add-rules     [{:rule/id :custom/require-jira-ticket
                    :rule/description 'Commit messages must reference a ticket'
                    :rule/category :workflow
                    :rule/severity :error
                    :rule/origin-type :manual}]}

  CLI:    miniforge policy compose <composition-spec.edn> [--output path]

  OUTPUTS:
  - .miniforge/policy-candidates.edn    (compile and derive modes)
  - .miniforge/packs/<name>.pack.edn    (all modes, after promotion)
  - .miniforge/policy-review.edn        (optional review decisions artifact)"

 :spec/intent {:type :feature
               :scope ["bases/cli/src"
                       "components/policy-pack/src"
                       "components/knowledge/src"
                       "components/llm/src"]}

 :spec/constraints
 ["Output must conform to the N4-delta candidate schema and existing .pack.edn schema"
  "Candidate extraction must be schema-stable and semantically reproducible under
   unchanged source material and compiler configuration, modulo ordering and
   bounded confidence jitter"
  "Document parsing must handle markdown, plaintext, and PDF at minimum"
  "Each candidate must have provenance per the N4-delta provenance contract"
  "Each candidate must declare origin-type: direct, inferred, composed, or manual"
  "Each candidate must declare enforceability: executable, heuristic, advisory, or human-review"
  "A candidate with enforceability human-review must not be silently upgraded to executable"
  "Compilation must produce candidate artifacts before pack artifacts"
  "Only accepted candidates may be promoted into compiled pack rules"
  "Compose mode must be pure and deterministic — no LLM calls"
  "Derive mode must support operation without LLM for machine-readable artifacts"
  "LLM calls must be budget-bounded (max tokens, max cost per compilation)"
  "Pack metadata must include compilation timestamp and source fingerprint set"
  "Must not require any miniforge-specific format in source documents"
  "Source fingerprinting must support changed-source detection for staleness"]

 :spec/acceptance-criteria
 ["miniforge policy compile <markdown-file> --emit candidates produces policy-candidates.edn"
  "miniforge policy compile <url> fetches and compiles a remote document"
  "miniforge policy compile --review opens interactive candidate review"
  "miniforge policy compile --promote emits .pack.edn from accepted candidates"
  "miniforge policy derive infers candidates from linter configs without LLM"
  "miniforge policy derive --enrich uses LLM to add descriptions to inferred candidates"
  "miniforge policy compose merges packs with overrides deterministically"
  "Every candidate has provenance linking to source with support-type and source-fingerprint"
  "Every candidate has origin-type and enforceability classification"
  "Candidate status begins as :proposed unless manually authored as :accepted"
  "Compiled packs load via policy-pack/load-all-packs without special handling"
  "Compilation of a 50-page style guide completes in under 5 minutes"
  "Duplicate candidates across source sections are merged with combined provenance"
  "Re-compilation of unchanged source produces semantically equivalent candidates"]

 :spec/workflow-type :canonical-sdlc}
